	public void appendHit(int hit) {
		hitDiff = hit;
		updateHp(hitDiff, false);
		hitUpdateRequired = true;
		updateRequired = true;
	}

	public void updateHp(int i, boolean flag) {
		if (!IsDead) {
 			if (flag) {
				NewHP += i;

				if (NewHP > getLevelForXP(playerXP[3])) {
					i = NewHP - getLevelForXP(playerXP[3]);
					NewHP = getLevelForXP(playerXP[3]);
				}
			} else if (!flag) {
				NewHP -= i;

				if (NewHP < 0) {
					NewHP = 0;
				}
			}
			playerLevel[3] = NewHP;
			NewHP = playerLevel[3];
			setSkillLevel(3, playerLevel[3], playerXP[3]);
		}
 	}

	public long stunDelay;
	public long thiefTimer;
	public int thiefDelay;
	public int thievingType;
	public boolean thiefNPC;
	public int ThiefNPC;[/code]

The 'GetBlockAnim' method simply sets your block animation for when you get hit by the Npc when failing a pickpocketing. In this method I use the 'for' statement to shorten codes such as:
[code]if (id == 1000 || id == 1001 || id == 1002 || id == 1003 || id == 1004 || id == 1005 || id == 1006 || id == 1007 || id == 1008 || id == 1009 || id == 1010) {
	return ####;
}[/code]

Which can be shortened to this:
[code]for (int i = 1000; i < 1011; i++) {
        if (id == i) {
                return ####;
        }
}[/code]

The 'appendHit' method is a shorter and simpler way to declare your character getting hit, and is used for when you get hit by the Npc when failing a pickpocketing. It sets the hitDiff variable to whatever the method's integer is set to, and then updates the first player hit mask - "hitUpdateRequired = true".

The 'updateHP' method is used in the 'appendHit' method, it is a simpler way to declare hp being depleted, and is my alternative than using the 'healing' boolean. The updateHP method may be used to both add and deplete HP with the 'flag' boolean declared within the method. If the 'flag' variable is set to [b]true[/b], then HP will be add onto the character's current HP. If the 'flag' variable is set to [b]false[/b], then HP will be depleted from the character's current HP. This method also updates the character's HitPoints skill integer on the stats interface, to whatever the current HP is - "setSkillLevel(3, playerLevel[3], playerXP[3]);".


[u][b]Step 3:[/b][/u]

Again, in client.java, in your 'process' method add these:

[code]		if (thievingType > 0 && thiefNPC) {
			if (GoodDistance(absX, absY, skillX, skillY, 1)) {
				ThievingHandler thief = new ThievingHandler(this);
				thief.ThiefStart(this);
			}
		}
		if (thiefDelay > 0) {
			thiefDelay--;
		}
		if (thiefDelay == 1) {
			ThievingHandler thief = new ThievingHandler(this);
			thief.ThiefFinish(this);
		}[/code]

The first of the three above calls the constructor within the ThievingHandler class to set the player's id, then calls the method to start pickpocketing when the thievingType exceeds 0, the thiefNPC boolean is set to true, and when you are within the distance of 1 square of the Npc you are pickpocketing.
The second of the three above simple depletes the 'thiefDelay' long by 1 each time the process method is called.
The third of the three above makes it so when the 'thiefDelay' long is equal to 1, then the finishing of pickpocketing is called.


[u][b]Step 4:[/b][/u]

At the top of packet 17 in client.java (Search 'case 17:' in client.java to find it) add this below 'case 17:':

[code]skillX = server.npcHandler.npcs[NPCSlot].absX;
skillY = server.npcHandler.npcs[NPCSlot].absY;
ThiefNPC = inStream.readUnsignedWordBigEndianA();[/code]

The 'skillX' and 'skillY' integers will equal to the Npc's coordinates which is used earlier in this tutorial.
The 'ThiefNPC' integer will equal to the identification of the NPC.

Next, add this:

[code]if (NPCID == 1) {
	thievingType = 1;
	thiefNPC = true;
}[/code]

This is the pickpocketing set-off for the 'Man' npc. This will attempt to pickpocket the man.


[u][b]Step 5:[/b][/u]

In NPC.java, add these methods:

[code]	public void TurnNPCTo(int pointX, int pointY) {
		FocusPointX = 2 * pointX + 1;
		FocusPointY = 2 * pointY + 1;
		FocusUpdateRequired = true;
	}

	public void requestText(String s) {
		textUpdate = s;
		textUpdateRequired = true;
		updateRequired = true;
	}[/code]

The 'TurnNPCTo' method sets the NPC's facing destination to your absX and absY, then updates the focus mask which updates the focus destination of the NPC.

The 'requestText' method simply shortens the 'code' used in my Handler. This method will use the force text mask to show text above an NPC's head, and in this case, it will be "What do you think you're doing?!" when you fail the pickpocket.


[u][b]Step 6:[/b][/u]

To add another NPC to pickpocket, simply add another

[code]if (NPCID == #) {
	thievingType = #;
	thiefNPC = true;
}[/code]

And in the ThievingHandler class, in the 'startPP' method add another:

[code]case NPCID:
	startPP(level Required, "Npc Name");
	break;[/code]

And again in the ThievingHandler, in the 'finishPP' method add another:

[code]case NPCID:
	finishPP(levelRequired, EXP, Money given, MAX hit from fail, "Npc name");
	break;[/code]



Hopefully I explained this tutorial well enough for you all to understand it correctly. Enjoy :).
